Guess no new cover edition.

Resource on what these spec terminology mean
https://www.nite-walker.com/post/2019/11/21/specs-for-dummies-101
https://apollogearco.com/blogs/news/night-vision-specs-explained
https://gloomgroup.com/blogs/night-vision-info/night-vision-specifications-understanding-what-they-mean

You shouldn't be chasing for spec values but they do exist and if you wanted to know what "better spec" values are there's a way to know which unit is desirable over another.
Most retailers won't post this info as they build NVDs to order, first come first serve, and depending on their grading scale of high, mid, low tier it may differ from retailers. If a retailer offer a “ready to ship” fully built units they will list the spec values. Hand select is an option from retailers that will try to match to your spec requirements.

Some reputable retailers:
https://www.jrhenterprises.com/
https://nvisionoptics.com/
https://www.customnightvision.com/
https://gooningear.com/
https://apollogearco.com
https://blackphasetactical.com/
https://steeleindustries.com/

SNR: signal to noise ratio, the amount of signal the tube can make compared to the noise
EBI: equivalent background information, how much false image appears in the screen through which the actual image has to show, sort of a noise floor of sorts
Halo: How big the circle of bloom is around lights
Photocathode Sensitivity: How sensitive the photocathode is
LP Resolution: Line pair res of the center of the image as measure against a standardized chart

If one spec is shit it negates the rest, if you have a halo of 2.0 it kinda fucks on an EBI of 0.20 if you want to do any kind of shooting and it's all a balance game

The numbers to meet or beat are
EBI under 1, preferably under 0.6 being great, 0.1 is gucci
Halo under 1, anything under 0.7 is awesome
SNR, over 25 anything over 30 is gucci
Photocathode, 1900+ is pretty great, 2500+ is stellar
Resolution of 64+ is good, 72+ is gucci

True. People like to use Pinochet as an example of how far right governments work best but Pinochet was an example of an authoritarian learning his flaws and ultimately dissolving said system after enemies and corrupt elements were removed. He was smart enough to recognize the shortcomings of these systems so let dissenting voices in as advisors and trialed their ideas. Some of his own polices proved pretty unproductive so he simply stepped aside and let outsiders figure stuff out for him and then stamped it with his endorsement if it proved to work. Also killed corrupt officials and sycophants whether they were on his side or the other side. In the end he left his fate up to objective election and stepped down when the national vote called for democracy. com:
Suppose you could send a huge shipment of whatever pistol you think is best, and ammo for them, back in time to equip a military that lost a battle or war.

Which handgun do you send, and what's the most recent battle/war that you think could have been turned by being equipped with it?

(can have accessories conventionally considered to be pistol accessories)

[{'no': 56358296, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)01:55:37', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>56355257
Hypothetical as fuck...

This first one is a hell of a stretch, but it's more about the thought exercise than anything. In reality, they would have still lost WW1 for a variety of other reasons, but it's possible they could have won some battles or marginally improved survivability just enough to make tactical gains and end some battles differently. Maybe they would have realized the advantage of equipping them to every line troop and taken to urban fighting or redrawn a post-war border, altered armistice terms - I'm not claiming to know, just a thought exercise.

WW1 - Glock 17 pistols issued to the majority of Central Powers front line troops. At range, ie trench to trench they'd want to use rifles... but during a charge, packing a pistol and fire when close enough to inflict damage. They would have moved faster vs carrying rifles, wouldn't have to cycle bolts and they'd be better suited for close combat in the trenches (right up until they meet a Yank with a 12g). This is assuming they make it past the artillery, machine guns, barbed wire, mud and everything else. They would have the ammunition (9mm), so they could keep them supplied. It's inevitable that some asshole fudd would buy one to sporterize somehow; I think they destroy historic antiques out of spite.

The Spanish-American War - Arming the Spanish (Highasfuck Point C9). Illiterate conscripts could theoretically keep them running in the field. Charging into a fusillade of 9mm from every enemy soldier at close range might have made them rethink their great adventure.

Indian Campaigns - Arming the Natives (Concealable, high capacity 9mm). Custer wouldn't be the only guy everyone remembers getting clapped. It would be uncomfortable pushing the trail of tears when you'd have multiple random natives opening up with 15+ round concealable pistols against a handful of dudes with single shot trapdoor carbines.

I don’t think you understand how this works. There is no such thing as “fair” in the animal kingdom, only “balanced.” This is why humans have going to such lengths to innovate— to overcome the natural, psychical disadvantages we have against other creatures by using tools and wit. By sacrificing those innovations, you are putting yourself at a disadvantage. If you accept them, then you are at an advantage. Even if you resign yourself to only using a steel spear, it means nothing if the spear is too long, or you hurl it at the creature, or drop down on the creature from above. You want something that will allow you to emulate having a pair of teeth.

If you really want a sporting good time, then you should face a boar, brown bear or elk headlong, depending on your level of moxy. Do NOT use a long spear. A javelin wielded in the hand or, unironically, a stabbing sword could work. I would also recommend having a dagger handy at the belt, and you may simply prefer to use this instead of a conventional weapon... That said, I should think this a suicidal course of action. Engines that are acceptably efficient at mach 3+ aren't much good at low speeds, and a catapult can only do so much to make up for the short runway. com: is there a theoretical limit to armor strength? could you make something as light as styrofoam stop a 50 bmg?
last_replies:
[{'no': 56355287, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)20:20:24', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>56352548
Theoretically? It becomes like that thought experiment of the invincible spear and the impenetrable shield. In practice? Yes. Especially when you start getting into higher velocity impacts, the mechanics start behaving less like the behavior of solids you and I know from our day to day lives and more like fluids. At that point the scales tip more towards density and thickness rather than material strength to stop things. This exacerbates the issue as finding stronger and stronger materials becomes way harder. Even with .50 BMG, it becomes hard to find strong enough materials which will absorb that energy and remain lightweight. Tank armors try to deal with this issue on a larger scale by using composite layouts designed to put as much lateral stress on the projectile as possible to get the most use out of your material but at the end of the day they still have to be thick arrays with dense materials. You’ll find that it’s way easier to chuck something dense really fast than to find a strong enough material to stop it with a limited mass allowance.', 'time': 1670721624, 'resto': 56352548}, {'no': 56356508, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)22:37:06', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>56355287
